                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">That solution would cause other problems too. Self-blurring mobs would give no exp. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I proposed a possible solution off the top of my head and I stand by it as an excellent solution in every case except for the self-blurring mobs, which I admitedly didnt think about.  However, an even better solution is to just keep a record of when a fight starts and stops using something other than who has agro right now  (i.e. outside of the agro list).  This would be even more fair since the monk who risked himself to battle a mob down to 25% but had to FD would still get credit for all the work that he put into getting the mob there where as the wizard that zones out (and ends the fight) then zones back in (and starts a new fight) to kill off a mob that's already at 5% health would get less reward since they are taking less risk.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">People would say "sorry, you can't use mem-blur because we'd lose exp". </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Who uses memblur after the tank has agro?  I have used it maybe once or twice to get myself off the agro list, but I have almost never needed to use it in any other situation.  The only times I have used it was when I was charming and wanted to heal the mob or we had a partial wipe, we needed time to recover, and I didn't want to have to chain mez.  Am I missing out on something cool with memblur?
<br />

<br />
In any case, storing a record of a fight initiation outside of the agro list would solve the thinking that memblur can't be used based on experience loss.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">People wouldn't be able to help out of group because they'd be stealing exp.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">SOE has always said that there are no camps in the game and that KSing was the only thing that was frowned upon.  Storing a record of who initiated the fight outside of the agro list would actually HELP with this situation.  In fact, you could have scenarios like the following:  <ol type="1"><li>Your group initiates the fight on a mob at 100% health and does more than 50% damage to the mob - FULL experience.<li>Your group initiates the fight on a mob at 100% health and does less than 50% damage to the mob because another group came along and started killing it as well - NO experience to either group.  You could even go so far as to have the mob lootable only by the group who initiated the fight.  This would make loot KSing non-existant, though it would be good to beta test this.  (yeah, right..)<li>Your group is cleaning up a train from a group that had to zone.  The fight is initiated with the mob at 30% health.  Your group does all the remaining damage and is awarded 30% of full experience since that's all it was possible to earn from a mob that was already 70% dead to start with.</ol>
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Etc, etc...</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">What other situations are there? Maybe I'm an ignorant n00b, but there aren't that many agro related issues in the game.  There's just a few big issues.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Belanar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">There aren't easy solutions to problems like that.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">I respectfully disagree.   That's an easy problem to solve with a little common sense and basic programing.  Keeping a record of when a fight begins and ends outside of the agro list shouldn't be a huge deal.  If memblur is a weapon that PCs use to save themselves and mobs use to bounce agro, then {agro|memblur} shouldn't be used as a way to determine when a fight started or stopped and it absolutely shouldn't be used as a way to determine who gets what amount of experience for a fight.  That is a fundamental flaw that will continue to cause problems until it's resolved and SOE is skipping this by trying to implement ultra-quick fixes to the problem like altering a mob's regen rate.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Trellium wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">There are also issues with griefing by mem blurring mobs so a group only gets 1/10th of their experience.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">These issues were there before.  Any random enchanter or bard based group could grief someone by bluring and killing the mob that someone else had engaged.  Using agro is a poor way to handle who gets exp.  I think the revised solution that was developed using Belanar's post would handle this situation well because it tracks the fight outside of any player's ability to alter it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Trellium wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">How pets do damage has to be included too - what happens when your pet dies and you cast another one? Is that experience gone? Charm breaks?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">I dont really think that charmed pets should be altered in terms of what experience they take as their cut.  I'm not really sure how that affects the agro list or memblurs either.  If you have a pet that gets killed by a mob it poofs and no exp is awarded.  I see no reason to change this either.  Perhaps I'm misunderstanding the question.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Trellium wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Your assumption is that you know exactly what is possible now, and what will be possible in the future (expansions etc) on the day you create your character. This is extrodinarily unlikely. Its also not unreasonable to assume that SOE would class balance for soloing at some point. I diasagree with any argument that decides that it is your fault if you don't know the exact ins and outs of your class for all 65 levels and AA's on the day you build it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Actually, my assumption is that you have a basic understanding of what each class is capable of doing at most levels of the game that people play.  I feel like this is a sound assumption.  I came to EQ late (more than 4 years after the game was originally released) and had plenty of friends both in RL and in game explain the basic concept of each character class.  Invariably, they would mention whether or not the class was something that was good at soloing, duoing, or grouping and how players of those classes did those things.  
<br />

<br />
This is simply a part of picking a class that fits your playstyle and it doesn't require that you know the ins and outs of your possible class for all 65 levels and ever AA.  For example, there's no AA, spell or level that changes the fact that an enchanter is a buffing/debuffing class that doesn't melee well, but is capable in both grouping and soloing situation because of it's ability to charm.  That's one sentence and it essentially tells you everything you need to know about what an enchanter is and does.  There are probably hundreds of ways to get that information before you actually start making an enchanter.
<br />

<br />
Furthermore, I seriously doubt that SOE will ever balance EQ for classes in terms of soloing.  I consider that concept highly unreasonable.  First of all, this is a MMORPG.  They want people to play in groups and raids.  That is why they do things to make grouping and raiding rewarding.  Why would they spend many hours overhauling basic class design thats 5 years old in some cases to make it possible for all classes to have 'equal' soloing ability?  It doesn't fit with the initial concept of the game and would take a lot of effort.  
<br />

<br />
Let's look at the two most recently added classes.  The Beastlord is one of the best soloing classes in the game, if not the best.  It allows you to have a pet, a nice line of slow spells, and the ability to heal yourself and your pet (uninterrupted if you have your pet tanking for you).  The Berserker has no pet and really no way of healing itself.  It's ability of soloing is almost nonexistant, but it does bring some very solid DPS to the table.
<br />

<br />
If anything SOE seems to want to pick up on something that's been very popular in WoW beta and have *something* that anyone can do if they only have an hour to log on and play.  This would probably be some kind of soloing.  My guess is that they would add a few 'deliver the mail' style quests for ever class or continue with changes like the bandaging rules change to give classes more ability to solo.  They would not take a class that could solo now and make it impossible for them to solo through some kind of balancing thing.  
<br />

<br />
Therefore, if you are playing a class that can't solo and you want to be able to solo, stop playing the class that cant and make one that can!  If it hurts, don't do it!  Whining about it for years won't help, but I guess that doesn't stop a lot of people from doing it.  It's a game.  If you aren't having fun with it then something is wrong.  You should find a new game to play.  If you keep playing and it's never gets fun for you, but you feel the need to whine about how unfair it is, then I reserve the right to say that you only have yourself to blame.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=811231" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.blaynesucks.com/images/Bellanfear.gif" border="0" /></a>
<br />
