        <tr>
                <td class="spaceRow" colspan="2" height="1"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/spacer.gif" alt="" width="1" height="1" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><a name="45534"></a><span class="name"><span class="usercolor">Bellanfear</span></span><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_offline.gif" border="0" align="absbottom" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /><div class="gensmall"><img src="images/ranks/rank_7.gif" alt="<b><center><font color=red>Sage</font></b></center>" title="<b><center><font color=red>Sage</font></b></center>" border="0" /><br /><b><center><font color=red>Sage</font></b></center></div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Joined:&nbsp;11 Jan 2004</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Total posts:&nbsp;843</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Location:&nbsp;Austin, TX</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Gender:&nbsp;Male</div></td>
                <td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=45534#45534"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu May 27, 2004 2:26 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=45534"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>AriuVilAki wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If the lowbie gets on the hate list at 97% he did, in essence, help take the mob down 97% unless you are actually suggesting that you only get xp for the <span style="font-weight: bold">damage</span> you do, in which case I don't agree with this proposal in any way shape or form -- just think how unbalancing this would be to the classes. DPS dinging left and right and clerics getting no xp at all!</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">I'm not talking about the traditional hate list or agro list.  I'm talking about a separate fight initiated list.  This would be a list the people/groups who agro'd the mob in order with the health of the mob at the time they first agro'd next to their names.  Exp is still awarded to a group as a whole and not to individuals of that group differently.  However, since this topic was broached in the context of soloing or PLing or otherwise cheating the exp system to get lots of reward with little risk, I have been discussing it from a single person's standpoint.  I'll run through a group example and hopefully that will help.
<br />

<br />
In this example there are two groups, the A group and the B group.  Each group has the following: ENC, CLR, WAR, ROG, BST, and WIZ.  Members are signified with their group letter after their class.
<br />

<br />
Let's say that group A engages a mob.  WARA pulls the mob.  BSTA and ROGA engage the mob.  WIZA nuke the mob.  ENCA slows the mob.  CLRA heals and thus agros the mob.  Now all of group A is on the fight initiated list until they zone out, die, or some arbitratry timelimit expires (say 30 mins?).  Let's say the oder they agro'd was soething like the following:  <ul><li>WARA - 100%<li>ROGA - 99%<li> BSTA - 99% <li> WIZA - 94% <li> ENCA - 93% <li> CLRA - 92%</ul>Since the group as a whole is treated as one unit and WARA initiated the fight at 100%, they have the chance to earn full experience for the fight.  Thus, the actual fight Initiated list would consist of one entry: <ul><li>Group A - 100%</ul>
<br />

<br />
Now group B comes along and wants to help out.  For the sake of argument we'll say that the first peron in group B agros the mob at 70% health.  This causes the actual fight initiated list to look like: <ul><li>Group A - 100%<li>Group B - 70%</ul>
<br />

<br />
From here there are several possible situations that could occur.  First let me state again that the key part of how this system works is: <span style="font-weight: bold">In order to get any experience for a mob, you have to be the highest person/group on the fight initiated list and deal over half of the remaining damage to that mob.</span>  Group A could do one of three things.  <ol type="1"><li>Kill the mob and do more than 50% of the remaining damage from when they "signed up" to kill the mob.<li>Kill the mob and do less than 50% of the remaining damage.<li>Die or Zone out leaving the mob alive and pulling themselves from the fight initiated list (since the mob won the fight).</ol>  If group A meets situation #1, then they get all the experience.  If group A meets situation #2, then NO ONE gets any experience.  If group A meets situation #3, then it falls to group B.  Group B has the same three situations facing them, but for them 50% of the remaining damage is only 35% of the overall health of the mob (assuming it doesn't heal itself).  However, the maximum experience that group B can earn is 70% of what they would have earned if they initiated the fight with a 100% healthy version of the mob.  Therefore, group B could meet situation #1 and get 70% experience by doing half the remaining damage (~35% of the mob's overall health).  They could meet situation #2 by failing to do more than half the remainging damage and killing the mob (if say Group A took the mob to 2% and wiped leaving group B to kill the mob off)  and NO ONE would get any experience.  They could also meet situation #3 and end up zoning or dying or otherwise losing.
<br />

<br />
If group A's situation #1 occurs, they get 100% of the maximum experience of the mob divided up to each group member in the same proportions that we get now.  If group B's situation occurs then they get 70% of the maximum experience of the mob divided up to each group member in the same proportion as we get now.  It is NOT DPS based.  The only damage factor that comes into play is the one that chooses between situation #1 and situation #2 for each group.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Arcady wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Or I go out an solo, my pet does 99% of the damage, charm breaks, I get 1 percent of the experience. of course my ex pet is down to 5% so I nuke him too and get another 5% of the total experience...</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Your pet is initiating the fight.  At the moment that happen your whole group takes that place on the fight initiated list.  In the case of charm soloing, that is you and your pet.  Your pet's damage is attributed to you as your group's DPS.  If you meet with situation #1, (i.e. your pet and you combine for more than half of the remaining damage needed to kill the mob) then you get experience according to what level of health the mob was at to begin with (probably 100%).  If you pet breaks charm, it has left the fight just the same way it would have left the fight had it been a warrior friend of yours that zoned out.  You are still on the fight initated list since you are still a part of your group.  (The last remaining part.)  If you can kill the mob and meet with situation #1 then you get the full experience divided up amonst your group (which is just you).  Therefore you can still charm, break and burn the original mob for full exp.
<br />

<br />
However, the case is different for the ex-pet.  If your exp pet is at 5% health and you charmed it at 100% health, then you were put on the hate list at 100% health and simply nuking it down from 5% to 0% would get you no experience since that would qualify as situation #2.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Advanced thinking for those who are really following this discussion:</span>  You COULD still get full experience for your ex-pet.  How??  You would have to heal it to 95% health and then deal party damage to it untill it was dead.  This party damage could be another charmed pet, a group of 5 people that you invited expressly for the purpose of killing the mob, or any other type of standard DPS that can be attributed to your party so long as you do not leave the fight initated list.  So the quetion you may be asking yourself is "why 95%?"  The answer is that when you charmed the mob you did so at 100% health and essentially said, I'm willing to do at least half of the necessary damage remaining to kill this mob.  Then you had your charmed pet attack something that did damage to it that was NOT attributed to your party.  (The damage in this scenario was attributed to the mob that you were fighting.)  That damage source did 95% of the mob's full health in damage.  Let's say that the mob has 10,000 HP when 100% healthy.  Thus you have the following:  <ul><li>Damage you have done - 0<li>Damage from outside your party - 9,500</ul>When you healed the mob to 95% health it went back to 9,500 HP.  Thus, if you could get your party to deal ALL of that damage you would end up with the following situation.<ul><li>Damage you have done - 9,500<li>Damage from outside your party - 9,500</ul>As you can see your party has now done 'half of the remaining damage needed to kill the mob' from the moment that your party was added to the fight initiated list and you would get full experience for the fight to divide amongst your party.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Arcady wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">And yes, PLing can still happen...The proper way to PL is to cast an HP buff, a high level DS and keep the character healed..</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">If you read what I said in my earlier post you woud have seen this:</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Bellanfear wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In terms of PLing, you'd have to be able to do more than half of the damage to the mob to get any exp regardless of your situation. This means that if you are being PL'd by a damage shield and you can't do more than half of the mob's damage yourself, then you won't get exp. Also, you would have to be highest on the fight initiated list, so if you are having a highbie pull singles for you, the highbie would have to zone to get off the fight initiated list for you to get exp.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Damage from a damage shield is currently assigned the same way as damage to a charmed pet from a mob that you are trying kill and it's possible to get experience from this kind of kill.  That is why you can currently PL using damage shields.  In my system, damage from a damage shield would be assigned either to the party if the caster of the DS was in your party or as damage done outside of your party if the caster is not in the party.  Now you might be a bit miffed because you say things like HP buffs and haste allow a character to create his own damage and thus they shouldn't 'count' either.  I agree.  <a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?p=35286#35286" target="_blank" class="postlink">Which is why I have said before (link)</a> that <span style="font-weight: bold">group buffs shouldn't be allowed to last more than 5-10 minutes after the person that cast them has left the raid or the group.</span>  They account for damage (think of them as accounting for 'utility' if you wish) in some way and shouldn't be attributed to a player that doesn't have a group member who cast those buffs.  It's an inherient imbalance in this game.  
<br />

<br />
However, I couldn't seem to make anyone in that thread understand it either.  Maybe if everyone thought of KEI as a 4.5 hour damage shield that increased the effectiveness of the person with the buff, then we wouldn't be so eager to sell out other members of our class by KEI whoring in PoK because it lessens the extra utility of spells like VoQ.  When everyone walks around with KEI, VoQ is a level 65 spell that effectively buffs for 4 mana/tick, 3 int, and 3 wis.  If no one could have group buffs last outside of the group they were cast in, then VoQ is a level 65 18 mana/tick, 28 int, and 28 wis buff.
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, the point is that with my simple change in the system, you would have to out damage a DS that you were using to help you kill a mob.  It would be useful in PLing, but not nearly to the extent that it was.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=811231" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.blaynesucks.com/images/Bellanfear.gif" border="0" /></a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=5628" target="_blank" class="postlink">E70.370/LT h+ 4.4kHP 6.2km ft15 G+++ e+++ o--- T+++ L++ H++(+++)@ f+++ g b c++++ t++++ D !X FP++ FG+ !FO E S- FE+ !TR !GT</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
